&gt; /*  Test Program  TestLanguageVector.java*/
&gt; /* This programs fails when i run a negative test. Plz go thro the comments
&gt; i have typed */
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; import junit.framework.*;
&gt; import java.util.*;
&gt; import java.io.*;

&gt; class TestLanguageVector extends TestCase {
&gt; 	LanguageVector langvect =new LanguageVector();
&gt; 	public void testlangvect(){
&gt; 	System.out.println(&quot;value of langvect.length&quot;+langvect.length);
&gt; 	assertEquals(2,langvect.length);
&gt; /* the assert fails when i give other value than 2, and the program throws
&gt; exception and stops, the next assertion is not tested and no FALIURE mssg
&gt; is given.*/
&gt; 	assertEquals(&quot;COBOL&quot;,langvect.list.elementAt(2));
&gt; 	}
&gt;
&gt; 	public static Test suite(){
&gt; 		return new TestSuite(&quot;TestLanguageVector.class&quot;);
&gt; 	}

Your suite, when it runs, runs testlangvect [better would be testLangVect], 
which makes a new empty vector, assigns it into langvect, and then
asserts that its length is 2. Since its length will be 0, you&#39;ll get a failure
[ie an exception is raised and caught by the junit machinery]. Because
the assert failed, the COBOL test isn&#39;t executed. (And since the vector
is empty, the COBOL test certainly won&#39;t succeed.)

&gt; 	public static void main(String args[])
&gt; 	{
&gt;
&gt; 	    String params[] = {&quot;TOMCAT&quot;,&quot;EJB&quot;};
&gt; /*I passs parameters to the main () of LanguageVector.java  */
&gt; 	    LanguageVector.main(params);

That call doesn&#39;t do anything useful with the test code. It fiddles around and
prints stuff out.

&gt; 	    /*1.If the below two stmts are not added the testlangvect() is not
&gt; 			getting innitaited */
&gt; 		/*2. If I run negative test the Faliure msg is not displayed
&gt; 		the program stops after throwing the first Exception  */
&gt;
&gt; 	    TestLanguageVector testlangVector= new TestLanguageVector();
&gt; 		testlangVector.testlangvect();

You&#39;re running the test outside the test framework, so assertion failures will
become exceptions. Don&#39;t do that. Run the test using the suite ...

&gt; 	    junit.textui.TestRunner.run(suite());

... as you do here. You need to decide what you actually want to test, and 
write a test for it. What *do* you want to test? I can&#39;t tell from the code what
you&#39;re trying to achieve. 

